Let $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ be the vector we want to project onto the plane. First, we need to find a normal vector to the plane. The plane is given by the equation $3x - y + 4z = 0$, so a normal vector is $\mathbf{n} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}$. Projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto the plane can be found by subtracting the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{n}$ from $\mathbf{v}$. The projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{n}$ is given by:
\begin{align*}
\text{proj}_{\mathbf{n}} \mathbf{v} &= \left(\frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}}{\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{n}}\right) \mathbf{n}
\end{align*}</think>
<answer>
To solve this, we need to calculate the dot product $\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}$ and the dot product $\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{n}$, and then use these to find the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{n}$.
The dot product $\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}$ is calculated as follows:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= (1)(3) + (2)(-1) + (3)(4) \\
&= 3 - 2 + 12 \\
&= 13
\end{align*}
Next, we calculate the dot product $\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{n}$:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{n} &= \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= (3)(3) + (-1)(-1) + (4)(4) \\
&= 9 + 1 + 16 \\
&= 26
\end{align*}
Thus, the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{n}$ can be found by:
\begin{align*}
\text{proj}_{\mathbf{n}} \mathbf{v} &= \left(\frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}}{\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{n}}\right) \mathbf{n} \\
&= \left(\frac{13}{26}\right) \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} \frac{3}{2} \\ -\frac{1}{2} \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
Finally, the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto the plane is given by:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} - \text{proj}_{\mathbf{n}} \mathbf{v} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} \frac{3}{2} \\ -\frac{1}{2} \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 1 - \frac{3}{2} \\ 2 + \frac{1}{2} \\ 3 - 2 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} -\frac{1}{2} \\ \frac{5}{2} \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
</answer>

